ProofThe proof of Theorem 3 is based on using the approach given in [30], [31], [32], [33]. It should be noted, first of all, that the second equation of (16) can be rewritten as (24)I˙=βe−τ(σ+μ)S(t)I(t)1+ωI(t)−(γ1+ϕ+μ+δ1)I(t)−ddt∫t−τtβe−τ(σ+μ)S(x)I(x)1+ωI(x)dx. Consider the following function: V(t)=I(t)+∫t−τtβe−τ(σ+μ)S(x)I(x)1+ωI(x)dx. Clearly, V(t) is bounded (since the variables I(t) and S(t) are bounded). Furthermore, it follows, using (24), that (25)V˙=βe−τ(σ+μ)S(t)I(t)1+ωI(t)−(γ1+ϕ+μ+δ1)I(t). Since, at the endemic steady state, S(t) is given by S∗∗=Πμ+βI∗∗1+ωI∗∗>0 whenever R0H>1, it is clear that for any 0<q<1,S∗∗<K, where K=Πμ+βqI∗∗1+ωqI∗∗. Hence, there exists a number m≥1 such that S∗∗<K(1−e−mΠτ/K).The next task is to show that I(t)≥qI∗∗ for all t≥(m+1)τ. Suppose, by contradiction, that I(t)<qI∗∗ for all t≥(m+1)τ. It then follows, from the first equation of (16), for t≥(m+1)τ, that S˙(t)>Π−(μ+βqI∗∗1+ωqI∗∗)S(t)=Π−ΠKS(t). Hence, S(t)>K−e−Π/K[t−(m+1)τ]{K−S[(m+1)τ]},>K{1−e−Π/K[t−(m+1)τ]}, and so, for t≥(2m+1)τ, (26)S(t)>K(1−e−mΠτ/K)=Sˆ>S∗∗.
Since I(t)<qI∗∗<I∗∗, it follows from (25), for t≥(2m+1)τ, that (27)V˙>βe−τ(μ+σ)S(t)I(t)1+ωI∗∗−(γ1+ϕ+μ+δ1)I(t),>βe−τ(μ+σ)SˆI(t)1+ωI∗∗−(γ1+ϕ+μ+δ1)I(t),=[βe−τ(μ+σ)Sˆ1+ωI∗∗−(γ1+ϕ+μ+δ1)]I(t). Let Iˆ=minθ∈[−τ,0]I(θ+2τ(m+1)). It can be claimed that I(t)≥Iˆ for all t≥(2m+1)τ. Suppose the claim does not hold. Then there exists a constant d1>0 such that I(t)≥Iˆ for t∈([2m+1]τ,2[m+1]τ+d1=t∗),I(t)<Iˆ for t>t∗ with I(t∗)=Iˆ and I˙(t∗)≤0 (see Fig. 6
). However, it follows from the third equation of (16), when t=t∗, that I˙(t∗)=e−τ(σ+μ)βS(t∗−τ)I(t∗−τ)1+ωI(t∗−τ)−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)I(t∗),=e−τ(σ+μ)βS(t∗−τ)I(t∗−τ)1+ωI(t∗−τ)−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)Iˆ,since I(t∗)=Iˆ,≥e−τ(σ+μ)βS(t∗−τ)Iˆ1+ωI(t∗−τ)−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)Iˆ,since I(t)≥Iˆ for t∈([2m+1]τ,t∗),>[e−τ(σ+μ)βS(t∗−τ)1+ωI∗∗−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)]Iˆ,since I(t)<I∗∗ for t≥(2m+1)τ,>[e−τ(σ+μ)βS∗∗1+ωI∗∗−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)]Iˆ=0. This contradicts the fact that I˙(t∗)≤0. Hence, I(t)≥Iˆ for t≥(2m+1)τ. Thus, it follows from (27) that V˙>[βe−τ(μ+σ)Sˆ1+ωI∗∗−(γ1+ϕ+μ+δ1)]Iˆfor all t≥2(m+1)τ. Hence, limt→∞V(t)=∞, which contradicts the fact that V(t) is bounded. Finally, to complete the proof, we need to show that I(t)≥ν for sufficiently large t.Let t1 be sufficiently large and I(t1)=qI∗∗. Consider the following interval, [t1,t2]. It follows, from the second equation of (16), that I˙≥−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)I. Hence, (28)I(t)>I(t1)e−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)(t−t1)=qI∗∗e−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)(t−t1),for t∈[t1,t2]. It is clear from (28) that if t2−t1≤τ, then I(t)≥qI∗∗e−τ(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)=qν. For the other case (where t2−t1>τ), it is easy to see that the inequity I(t)≥qI∗∗e−τ(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)=qν also holds for t∈[t1,t1+τ]. We claim that (28) also holds for t∈(t1+τ,t2]. If not, then there exists a constant d>0 such that I(t)≥qν for t∈(t1+τ,t1+τ+d=t0), with I(t0)=qν,I(t)<qν for t∈(t0,t2) and I˙(t0)≤0. Here, too, it follows from the third equation of (16), when t=t0, that I˙(t0)=e−τ(σ+μ)βS(t0−τ)I(t0−τ)1+ωI(t0−τ)−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)I(t0),=e−τ(σ+μ)βS(t0−τ)I(t0−τ)1+ωI(t0−τ)−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)qν,since I(t0)=qν,≥e−τ(σ+μ)βS(t0−τ)qν1+ωqν−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)qν,since I(t)≥qν,≥[e−τ(σ+μ)βS(t0−τ)1+ωI∗∗−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)]qν,since qν≤I∗∗,>[e−τ(σ+μ)βS∗∗1+ωI∗∗−(ϕ+γ1+μ+δ1)]qν=0. This contradicts the fact that I˙(t0)≤0. Hence, I(t)≥qν for t∈[t1,t1]. Since this interval and the parameter q∈(0,1) are chosen arbitrarily, it is concluded that I(t)≥ν. Thus, lim inft→∞I(t)≥ν. □

To assess the impact of using time delay to model the incubation period on the suitability of the model (3) for realistically capturing the observed SARS data (cumulative probable cases) for the Greater Toronto Area (GTA) of Canada, the model (3) is simulated in the presence and absence of time delay. It should be stated that the GTA recorded about 250 probable cases of SARS during the 2003 outbreaks [21]. The simulation results obtained, depicted in Fig. 9
, show that while the model without time delay (considered in [10]) underestimated the observed cumulative number of probable cases (about 170 cases), the model with time delay (i.e., model (3)) gave a good estimate of the observed data (about 220 cases). Thus, this study suggests that the model (3), with time delay, is more appropriate for modeling the SARS outbreaks in the GTA than the corresponding model without time delay (given in [10]). Similar simulation results were obtained for the case of the model with Holling type II function (16) (see Fig. 10
).
